Objective : Predict the likelihood of a loan to be "charged off" based on provided variables¶

2. Target variable exploration¶

Since we are predicting this variable we want to know the different status for loans to better understand the variable

In [99]:
#getting the % of each category for loan status
loan_df['loan_status'].value_counts(normalize=True,dropna=False)*100
Out[99]:
Fully Paid           70.50
Charged Off          17.55
Current              11.32
Late (31-120 days)    0.39

Late (16-30 days)     0.07
Default               0.00
Name: loan_status, dtype: float64

We are going to keep the loans that have the status of "Fully paid" or "Charged Off" to learn the differences between the two categories. We will drop the "Current" category as it represents loans that are in good standing for re-payment and might not yield useful information as the loan is still active. Next we will also delete records related to the remaing four loan status types as they represent less than 1% of the categories together and will not significantly alter the data.

In [496]:
loan_df = loan_df.loc[loan_df['loan_status'].isin(['Fully Paid', 'Charged Off'])]

There ae 176,081 loans remaining but we can see that only 20% of the loans were charged off leading to class imbalance when we train a machine learning model. We will account for this imbalance by properly adding weights to each category before training.

3. Limiting the feature space¶

The dataset has over 148 features for each loan. It does not make sense to include all of them as is. The prediction model will be weaker if we include all the variables and hence we will drop features in three steps:

   1.Drop features with more than 20% of their data missing

   2.Drop features that are not easily understood as to what they contain through manual inspection of variable name

   3.Drop features that are highly correlated

Reference: https://www.dummies.com/article/academics-the-arts/math/statistics/how-to-interpret-a-correlation-coefficient-r-169792/

There is correlation between certain numerical features. Here we consider variables with correlations greater than 0.70 to be highly correlated. The variables with high correlation are:

a)loan_amnt and installment : 0.95 
b)last_fico_range_high and last_fico_range_high:0.83

The high correlations are as expected. The installment is dependent on the loan amount and the fico scores are also related as it is for the same individual. We will drop the installment variable and handle the fico score related variables at a later stage

5 Pre-processing¶

5.1 Converting categorical columns to dummy variables¶

5.2 Convert loan status to 0/1 indicator¶

0 indicates fully paid and 1 indicates that the loan was charged off

In [522]:
loan_df['loan_status'] = loan_df['loan_status'].replace(to_replace=['Fully Paid', 'Charged Off'], value=[0, 1])

6 Model Training and Evaluation¶

We will build the models using the following algorithms and evaluate them

1) Logistic Regression
2) Random Forest

8 Limitations and Conclusion¶

In this project we used the given variables to build machine learning models with good accuracy. Although both logistic and random forest performed well we still have to consider the results with a grain of salt as not all the features were utilized. Some features were dropped because of missing values which were beyond imputation, but we excluded certain variables because of the lack of data dictionary.Including more variables might help in making the model more robust and accurate and should be tested before we accept the above results.

From our exploratory analysis we noticed that borrowers whose loans were charged off have higher debt to income ratio,higher credit card utilization, lower credit scores, mostly do not own their homes and have shorter credit history compared to borrowers who have completely paid off the loans. Since these variables explain the loan status to a great extent I believe that was the reason for very good prediction models we see above.
